<H2><A id=3Deffects name=3Deffects></A>Scroll messages and effects</H2>
<P>(Adapted from the spoiler "scrolls", by Ian Burrell.)</P>
<P>In order to read a scroll, you must either be unblind or know the =
APPEARANCE=20
of the scroll. When a scroll is read, it will be used up and disappear =
(except=20
blank paper). The effects depend on the blessing of the scroll. =
Non-cursed means=20
either blessed or uncursed. If you are confused while reading the =
scroll, "you=20
mispronounce the magic words" and may obtain a different effect. Some =
scrolls=20
have a different message for "beginners"; a character is considered a =
beginner=20
until accumulating 2000 score points (1000 for Wizards).</P>
<H3><A id=3Damnesia name=3Damnesia></A>amnesia</H3>
<P>All Sokoban maps are immune from the effects of amnesia.</P>
<P><STRONG>cursed or you are NOT confused</STRONG> <BR>You forget all of =
the=20
current level.</P>
<P><STRONG>non-cursed and confused</STRONG> <BR>You forget 6/7 of the =
current=20
level.</P>
<P>In addition, if <STRONG>uncursed or cursed</STRONG> <BR>You forget =
any number=20
of spells.</P>
<P>In every case, <BR>You have a 1/3 chance of forgetting up to 25% of =
all known=20
level maps and a separate 1/3 chance of forgetting up to 25% of object=20
identities. <BR>You forget all traps on your current level, forget =
whether you=20
are punished, and abuse your wisdom.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE class=3Ddl>
  <P>"Your mind releases itself from mundane concerns." (hallucinating) =
<BR>"As=20
  your mind turns inward on itself, you forget everything else." (your=20
  character's name is Maud); <BR>"Who was that Maud person anyway?" =
(otherwise,=20
  50%) <BR>"Thinking of Maud you forget everything else." (otherwise,=20
50%)</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The scroll is (re-)identified.</P>
<H3><A id=3Dblank_paper name=3Dblank_paper>blank paper</A></H3>
<P>You identify the scroll; it will not be used up. <BR></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE class=3Ddl>
  <P>"This scroll seems to be blank." (unblind) <BR>"You don't remember =
there=20
  being any magic words on this scroll." (blind)</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
